_continued\": \"The disparities extend beyond individual countries to regional aggregates. Lower middle income countries averaged 610 MMR, while low and middle income countries overall averaged 443 MMR [Data: Entities (2431, 2710)]. These aggregate figures mask the extreme variation within income categories, suggesting that income classification alone is insufficient for understanding maternal health outcomes. The Middle East and North Africa region averaged 345 MMR [Data: Entities (8859)], indicating regional patterns that warrant targeted policy interventions.\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Sub-Saharan African crisis in maternal mortality\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sub-Saharan Africa emerges as the region with the most severe maternal mortality crisis in 1988. Seven of the twelve individual countries in the dataset are African nations, and six of these rank among the world's highest MMR values [Data: Entities (4189, 7064, 4911, 5467, 8217, 2271)]. Democratic Republic of the Congo (824), Equatorial Guinea (675), Cameroon (559), and Burkina Faso (806) all exceeded 500 deaths per 100,000 live births [Data: Entities (4189, 7064, 4911, 2271)]. These rates reflect limited access to prenatal care, skilled birth attendance, and emergency obstetric services characteristic of the region during this period.\",\n            \"explanation_continued\": \"The African data points are consistently linked to 1988 through the relationships dataset, establishing temporal consistency [Data: Relationships (6183, 10277, 7141, 7898, 3262, +more)]. The concentration of high-mortality African nations in this dataset underscores the disproportionate burden of maternal mortality on the African continent and highlights the urgent need for healthcare system strengthening and resource allocation to address preventable maternal deaths.\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Stark contrast between developed and developing nation outcomes\",\n           